[
    {
        "index": 1,
        "start_time": 7785,
        "end_time": 9304,
        "text": "In the world of math,"
    },
    {
        "index": 2,
        "start_time": 9304,
        "end_time": 13384,
        "text": "many strange results are possible \nwhen we change the rules."
    },
    {
        "index": 3,
        "start_time": 13384,
        "end_time": 17226,
        "text": "But there\u2019s one rule that most of us \nhave been warned not to break:"
    },
    {
        "index": 4,
        "start_time": 17226,
        "end_time": 19605,
        "text": "don\u2019t divide by zero."
    },
    {
        "index": 5,
        "start_time": 19605,
        "end_time": 22584,
        "text": "How can the simple combination \nof an everyday number"
    },
    {
        "index": 6,
        "start_time": 22584,
        "end_time": 26463,
        "text": "and a basic operation \ncause such problems?"
    },
    {
        "index": 7,
        "start_time": 26463,
        "end_time": 29693,
        "text": "Normally, dividing by smaller \nand smaller numbers"
    },
    {
        "index": 8,
        "start_time": 29693,
        "end_time": 32321,
        "text": "gives you bigger and bigger answers."
    },
    {
        "index": 9,
        "start_time": 32321,
        "end_time": 34844,
        "text": "Ten divided by two is five,"
    },
    {
        "index": 10,
        "start_time": 34844,
        "end_time": 36443,
        "text": "by one is ten,"
    },
    {
        "index": 11,
        "start_time": 36443,
        "end_time": 39022,
        "text": "by one-millionth is 10 million,"
    },
    {
        "index": 12,
        "start_time": 39022,
        "end_time": 39980,
        "text": "and so on."
    },
    {
        "index": 13,
        "start_time": 39980,
        "end_time": 42291,
        "text": "So it seems like if you divide by numbers"
    },
    {
        "index": 14,
        "start_time": 42291,
        "end_time": 44900,
        "text": "that keep shrinking \nall the way down to zero,"
    },
    {
        "index": 15,
        "start_time": 44900,
        "end_time": 48061,
        "text": "the answer will grow \nto the largest thing possible."
    },
    {
        "index": 16,
        "start_time": 48061,
        "end_time": 52723,
        "text": "Then, isn\u2019t the answer to 10 \ndivided by zero actually infinity?"
    },
    {
        "index": 17,
        "start_time": 52723,
        "end_time": 54683,
        "text": "That may sound plausible."
    },
    {
        "index": 18,
        "start_time": 54683,
        "end_time": 57733,
        "text": "But all we really know is \nthat if we divide 10"
    },
    {
        "index": 19,
        "start_time": 57733,
        "end_time": 60674,
        "text": "by a number that tends towards zero,"
    },
    {
        "index": 20,
        "start_time": 60674,
        "end_time": 63734,
        "text": "the answer tends towards infinity."
    },
    {
        "index": 21,
        "start_time": 63734,
        "end_time": 67864,
        "text": "And that\u2019s not the same thing as\nsaying that 10 divided by zero"
    },
    {
        "index": 22,
        "start_time": 67864,
        "end_time": 70514,
        "text": "is equal to infinity."
    },
    {
        "index": 23,
        "start_time": 70514,
        "end_time": 71833,
        "text": "Why not?"
    },
    {
        "index": 24,
        "start_time": 71833,
        "end_time": 76222,
        "text": "Well, let\u2019s take a closer look \nat what division really means."
    },
    {
        "index": 25,
        "start_time": 76222,
        "end_time": 78574,
        "text": "Ten divided by two could mean,"
    },
    {
        "index": 26,
        "start_time": 78574,
        "end_time": 82671,
        "text": "&quot;How many times must \nwe add two together to make 10,\u201d"
    },
    {
        "index": 27,
        "start_time": 82671,
        "end_time": 86113,
        "text": "or, \u201ctwo times what equals 10?\u201d"
    },
    {
        "index": 28,
        "start_time": 86113,
        "end_time": 90453,
        "text": "Dividing by a number is essentially \nthe reverse of multiplying by it,"
    },
    {
        "index": 29,
        "start_time": 90453,
        "end_time": 92401,
        "text": "in the following way:"
    },
    {
        "index": 30,
        "start_time": 92401,
        "end_time": 95423,
        "text": "if we multiply any number \nby a given number x,"
    },
    {
        "index": 31,
        "start_time": 95423,
        "end_time": 99653,
        "text": "we can ask if there\u2019s a new number \nwe can multiply by afterwards"
    },
    {
        "index": 32,
        "start_time": 99653,
        "end_time": 102286,
        "text": "to get back to where we started."
    },
    {
        "index": 33,
        "start_time": 102286,
        "end_time": 107344,
        "text": "If there is, the new number is called \nthe multiplicative inverse of x."
    },
    {
        "index": 34,
        "start_time": 107344,
        "end_time": 111445,
        "text": "For example, if you multiply \nthree by two to get six,"
    },
    {
        "index": 35,
        "start_time": 111445,
        "end_time": 115564,
        "text": "you can then multiply \nby one-half to get back to three."
    },
    {
        "index": 36,
        "start_time": 115564,
        "end_time": 119394,
        "text": "So the multiplicative inverse \nof two is one-half,"
    },
    {
        "index": 37,
        "start_time": 119394,
        "end_time": 123964,
        "text": "and the multiplicative inverse \nof 10 is one-tenth."
    },
    {
        "index": 38,
        "start_time": 123964,
        "end_time": 129234,
        "text": "As you might notice, the product of any\nnumber and its multiplicative inverse"
    },
    {
        "index": 39,
        "start_time": 129234,
        "end_time": 131264,
        "text": "is always one."
    },
    {
        "index": 40,
        "start_time": 131264,
        "end_time": 133463,
        "text": "If we want to divide by zero,"
    },
    {
        "index": 41,
        "start_time": 133463,
        "end_time": 135843,
        "text": "we need to find \nits multiplicative inverse,"
    },
    {
        "index": 42,
        "start_time": 135843,
        "end_time": 139144,
        "text": "which should be one over zero."
    },
    {
        "index": 43,
        "start_time": 139144,
        "end_time": 144972,
        "text": "This would have to be such a number that\nmultiplying it by zero would give one."
    },
    {
        "index": 44,
        "start_time": 144972,
        "end_time": 149143,
        "text": "But because anything multiplied\nby zero is still zero,"
    },
    {
        "index": 45,
        "start_time": 149143,
        "end_time": 151556,
        "text": "such a number is impossible,"
    },
    {
        "index": 46,
        "start_time": 151556,
        "end_time": 154842,
        "text": "so zero has no multiplicative inverse."
    },
    {
        "index": 47,
        "start_time": 154842,
        "end_time": 157343,
        "text": "Does that really settle things, though?"
    },
    {
        "index": 48,
        "start_time": 157343,
        "end_time": 160983,
        "text": "After all, mathematicians \nhave broken rules before."
    },
    {
        "index": 49,
        "start_time": 160983,
        "end_time": 162713,
        "text": "For example, for a long time,"
    },
    {
        "index": 50,
        "start_time": 162713,
        "end_time": 166774,
        "text": "there was no such thing as taking \nthe square root of negative numbers."
    },
    {
        "index": 51,
        "start_time": 166774,
        "end_time": 170861,
        "text": "But then mathematicians defined \nthe square root of negative one"
    },
    {
        "index": 52,
        "start_time": 170861,
        "end_time": 173284,
        "text": "as a new number called i,"
    },
    {
        "index": 53,
        "start_time": 173284,
        "end_time": 177803,
        "text": "opening up a whole new\nmathematical world of complex numbers."
    },
    {
        "index": 54,
        "start_time": 177803,
        "end_time": 179245,
        "text": "So if they can do that,"
    },
    {
        "index": 55,
        "start_time": 179245,
        "end_time": 181203,
        "text": "couldn\u2019t we just make up a new rule,"
    },
    {
        "index": 56,
        "start_time": 181203,
        "end_time": 185264,
        "text": "say, that the symbol infinity \nmeans one over zero,"
    },
    {
        "index": 57,
        "start_time": 185264,
        "end_time": 187543,
        "text": "and see what happens?"
    },
    {
        "index": 58,
        "start_time": 187543,
        "end_time": 188593,
        "text": "Let&#39;s try it,"
    },
    {
        "index": 59,
        "start_time": 188593,
        "end_time": 191723,
        "text": "imagining we don\u2019t know \nanything about infinity already."
    },
    {
        "index": 60,
        "start_time": 191723,
        "end_time": 194292,
        "text": "Based on the definition \nof a multiplicative inverse,"
    },
    {
        "index": 61,
        "start_time": 194292,
        "end_time": 198474,
        "text": "zero times infinity must be equal to one."
    },
    {
        "index": 62,
        "start_time": 198474,
        "end_time": 204530,
        "text": "That means zero times infinity plus\nzero times infinity should equal two."
    },
    {
        "index": 63,
        "start_time": 204530,
        "end_time": 206487,
        "text": "Now, by the distributive property,"
    },
    {
        "index": 64,
        "start_time": 206487,
        "end_time": 209388,
        "text": "the left side of the equation \ncan be rearranged"
    },
    {
        "index": 65,
        "start_time": 209388,
        "end_time": 212619,
        "text": "to zero plus zero times infinity."
    },
    {
        "index": 66,
        "start_time": 212619,
        "end_time": 216188,
        "text": "And since zero plus zero \nis definitely zero,"
    },
    {
        "index": 67,
        "start_time": 216188,
        "end_time": 220049,
        "text": "that reduces down to zero times infinity."
    },
    {
        "index": 68,
        "start_time": 220049,
        "end_time": 223717,
        "text": "Unfortunately, we\u2019ve already defined \nthis as equal to one,"
    },
    {
        "index": 69,
        "start_time": 223717,
        "end_time": 228353,
        "text": "while the other side of the equation \nis still telling us it\u2019s equal to two."
    },
    {
        "index": 70,
        "start_time": 228353,
        "end_time": 231238,
        "text": "So, one equals two."
    },
    {
        "index": 71,
        "start_time": 231238,
        "end_time": 234464,
        "text": "Oddly enough, \nthat&#39;s not necessarily wrong;"
    },
    {
        "index": 72,
        "start_time": 234464,
        "end_time": 238132,
        "text": "it&#39;s just not true \nin our normal world of numbers."
    },
    {
        "index": 73,
        "start_time": 238132,
        "end_time": 240714,
        "text": "There\u2019s still a way it could\nbe mathematically valid,"
    },
    {
        "index": 74,
        "start_time": 240714,
        "end_time": 245221,
        "text": "if one, two, and every other number \nwere equal to zero."
    },
    {
        "index": 75,
        "start_time": 245221,
        "end_time": 247714,
        "text": "But having infinity equal to zero"
    },
    {
        "index": 76,
        "start_time": 247714,
        "end_time": 252884,
        "text": "is ultimately not all that useful \nto mathematicians, or anyone else."
    },
    {
        "index": 77,
        "start_time": 252884,
        "end_time": 256114,
        "text": "There actually is something called \nthe Riemann sphere"
    },
    {
        "index": 78,
        "start_time": 256114,
        "end_time": 259409,
        "text": "that involves dividing by zero \nby a different method,"
    },
    {
        "index": 79,
        "start_time": 259409,
        "end_time": 261773,
        "text": "but that\u2019s a story for another day."
    },
    {
        "index": 80,
        "start_time": 261773,
        "end_time": 265965,
        "text": "In the meantime, dividing by zero \nin the most obvious way"
    },
    {
        "index": 81,
        "start_time": 265965,
        "end_time": 267733,
        "text": "doesn\u2019t work out so great."
    },
    {
        "index": 82,
        "start_time": 267733,
        "end_time": 270674,
        "text": "But that shouldn\u2019t stop us \nfrom living dangerously"
    },
    {
        "index": 83,
        "start_time": 270674,
        "end_time": 273605,
        "text": "and experimenting \nwith breaking mathematical rules"
    },
    {
        "index": 84,
        "start_time": 273605,
        "end_time": 277483,
        "text": "to see if we can invent \nfun, new worlds to explore."
    }
]